{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17624967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17624967"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:20:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:20:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16957"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16957"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.59,0.07,0.02,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9647"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68671"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9647"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16957"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54128"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"9856"},{"type":"tags","id":"10290"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22761"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22765"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68671"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPurkinje fibres are specialized cardiac cells that form part of the heart\u0027s electrical conduction system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a key characteristic of Purkinje fibres?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rapid spontaneous depolarisation rate","Rapid conduction velocity of 2-4 m/s","High density of contractile proteins","Low glycogen content","Limited gap junction connections"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPurkinje fibres have a \u003Cstrong\u003Erapid conduction velocity of 2-4 m/s\u003C/strong\u003E, which is essential for coordinated ventricular contraction. This rapid conduction is facilitated by their large diameter and extensive gap junctions between cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh density of contractile proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - Purkinje fibres actually have fewer myofibrils than working cardiomyocytes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid spontaneous depolarisation rate\u003C/strong\u003E - Purkinje fibres have the ability to act as pacemaker cells, with an inherent rate of approximately 20-40 beats/minute. This is much slower than the sinoatrial node (rate 60-100) and the atrioventricular node (40-70 beats/min). \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELimited gap junction connections\u003C/strong\u003E - Purkinje fibres have abundant gap junctions to facilitate rapid conduction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow glycogen content\u003C/strong\u003E - Purkinje fibres have high glycogen content compared to working cardiomyocytes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe specialized features of Purkinje fibres allow them to rapidly conduct electrical signals from the bundle branches to the ventricular myocardium, ensuring synchronized contraction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Purkinje fibres conduct action potentials rapidly through the ventricles at 2-4 m/s to enable coordinated contraction.","The large diameter and extensive gap junctions of Purkinje fibres facilitate rapid electrical conduction."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54128"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16957"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54128"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T09:54:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T09:55:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9647"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68671"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovascular","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:3